Do you need to renew your car tags? Follow these simple instructions to do it online!

Renewing online by using https://secure.kentucky.gov/kytc/renewal. Enter your vehicle title number, license plate number, and credit card number. Vehicles that cannot be renewed online are: Vehicles with expired registrations, leased vehicles, vehicles without current insurance, or vehicles that are owned by someone who has overdue property taxes on ANY vehicle;

Of course, you can always mail your unexpired registration(s) to the office address: 103 South Main Street, Room 120, Versailles, KY 40383.

Please call the County Clerks Office with any questions or to make and appointment (859)873-3421

post_text: Woodford County is excited to announce that John "Bear" E. Coyle will be inducted into the Woodford County Public Schools Hall of Fame, Class of 2020. Coyle served Woodford County in public office from 1986 until his death in 2018. In 1992 John Coyle was named Kentucky‚Äôs Deputy Sheriff of the Year. He was then twice elected as Woodford County Sheriff. He moved on to serve as County Judge/Executive for 12 years and led the county through many great challenges and developments. During Coyle's time as Judge/Executive, he was able to effectively double the size of the Woodford County Park. John Coyle‚Äôs legacy continues to live on, and we thank him for his dedication and service to the people of Woodford County.
text: Woodford County is excited to announce that John "Bear" E. Coyle will be inducted into the Woodford County Public Schools Hall of Fame, Class of 2020. Coyle served Woodford County in public office from 1986 until his death in 2018. In 1992 John Coyle was named Kentucky‚Äôs Deputy Sheriff of the Year. He was then twice elected as Woodford County Sheriff. He moved on to serve as County Judge/Executive for 12 years and led the county through many great challenges and developments. During Coyle's time as Judge/Executive, he was able to effectively double the size of the Woodford County Park. John Coyle‚Äôs legacy continues to live on, and we thank him for his dedication and service to the people of Woodford County.

post_text:
VOTE Woodford County! Have you voted yet? Please don't wait until tomorrow! You can come to the Courthouse today and vote In-Person anytime up until 4pm.

You can also request your ballot and vote curbside at the Courthouse. Yes, that's right! We are full service at the Courthouse with Curbside voting.

For those who requested absentee ballots, please return your ballot in the mail or DROP OFF at the Courthouse in the secured Ballot Box AS SOON AS POSSIBLE. Please get your ballots in!

Tomorrow is election day, June 23rd. Falling Springs and the Courthouse will be in house voting locations from 6am to 6pm.

Important Note: We will not know the final official election results tomorrow night because of absentee balloting.

Woodford County is in the running to be the highest voter turnout in Kentucky. Please do your part and VOTE Woodford County! #WoodfordVotes

shared_text:
Judge/Executive James Kay
June 19 at 11:28 AM ¬∑

Expanding quality internet service to our rural areas of Woodford County has been one of my priorities as your Judge. I have been working with Scott and Bourbon Counties for months now on one of the first regional broadband initiatives in all of Kentucky. Our project moved forward today, as I am pleased to report the Kentucky Agricultural Development Board approved the first phase of funding for our regional broadband project focusing on our unserved and under-served rural areas of Woodford, Scott and Bourbon counties. We are working with the Bluegrass Area Development District (BGADD) on regional collaboration and providing technical advice. During the pandemic, we have seen the need to have quality internet everywhere, and I am committed to working on it for everywhere in Woodford County. #RuralBroadband

post_text: Juneteenth also known as "Freedom Day" commemorates of the ending of slavery in the United States. On June 19th 1865, the Union Army informed the last remaining slaves that the Civil War had ended and that all slaves were now free, more than two years after the Emancipation Proclamation. Today we honor and celebrate the day all black Americans became liberated from enslavement, and we continue to work towards racial equality and equal justice for all.

post_text: Thanks to our Maintenance Director Rick Wade for all his work for Woodford County #WofoProud
shared_text:
Woodford County Tourism Commission
June 8 at 12:01 PM ¬∑

Our next UnSung Hero is County employee Rick Wade!

Here is what a colleague had to say about Rick Wade.

Mr. Wade is the maintenance director for the Woodford County Fiscal Court and his duties extend to nearly every county owned property from the Courthouse to the Jouett House. He has worked tirelessly since March to ensure Woodford County employees have clean workspace to carry out their tasks and continues to incorporate physical changes to allow better delivery of services to the community. As if that weren't enough to keep him busy in addition to his normal responsibilities, Rick is overseeing the startup of a multi-million dollar energy efficiency project. Rick is a shining example of how to be a public employee.

post_text:
Woodford County EMS Station No. 1 on Big Sink Pike is ready for move in ahead of schedule!

Judge/Executive James Kay said, "Director Freeman Bailey put his heart and soul into this project and Woodford County can be proud of our new world-class EMS headquarters. Station No.1 will be one of the most energy efficient buildings in Woodford County, coming in on budget and ahead of schedule. " Kay added, "Our EMS crews are world-class and now our team has a quality facility to better serve our people."

Judge Kay applauded the great professional work done by Marrillia Design and Construction, thanking Owner Josh Marrillia, Site Manager Pete Hubbard and Project Manager Jim Hayes (a Woodford County resident) on a job well done. "They were awesome to work with. We couldn't ask for a better partner. Marrillia is a leader in their field and the quality of their professionalism, people and product is unmatched."

EMS crews are expected to move in the building this week. This project was one of the first priorities of the Fiscal Court. #WofoProud

post_text:
Today we honor Woodford County‚Äôs fallen heroes and all those who made the ultimate sacrifice for our Country. They represent links in an unbroken chain stretching all the way back to the Revolutionary War. We thank every brave man and woman serving at home or abroad, and their families who share in this selfless sacrifice. We are truly grateful for every Veteran who answered the call and served our great Nation. We are stronger and better for your service and sacrifice for our people. Woodford County proudly supports, honors and appreciates our military men and women and our Veterans. We pause today to reflect on the lives taken in defense of our freedom. We honor and thank the families of our fallen heroes who gave it all for our beloved Country.

God bless America and may God protect and keep those in harm's way. Have a happy and blessed Memorial Day #WoodfordHeroes

Falling Springs / Versailles -Woodford Parks & Rec is sharing a COVID-19 Update.
May 18 at 10:03 AM ¬∑

FALLING SPRINGS UPDATE - REOPENING

- As you have probably seen, the governor has announced that fitness centers, lap pools and therapy pools may reopen on June 1st. While this announcement has been made, the requirements to reopen have not yet been posted.

- We are are planning to reopen theses facilities at Falling Springs on June 1. We have a tentative reopening plan in place and will update and modify it as needed once the requirements are made available to us.

- Please be patient - we are as anxious to reopen as you are! Once we have details, we'll post all reopening plans and parameters on our website and on all of our social media platforms.

- Until we see you again, be safe and be kind!

*No information has been provided by the state regarding when recreational aquatic centers like the outdoor splash pool can reopen. No decisions have been or can be made until more information is provided by the state.

post_text: Happy Mother's Day Woodford County! Our community is home to so many wonderful moms. We thank every mother out there for your unconditional love and tireless care for your family. Woodford County values the strength, spirit and sacrifice it takes to raise a child. We commend you and thank you. Our hearts are with everyone missing their mother today. We love to see the positivity and joy of Mother's Day spreading across social media, drowning out the usual negativity. The power of a Mother's love is amazing. We wish a happy and blessed Mother's Day to you and your family.

post_text: Thank you to our amazing correctional officers and support staff at the Woodford County Detention Center. Jailer Rankin and her team work 24/7 365 days a year under challenging and stressful conditions to keep us safe. In these times, correctional facilities are ground zero for Covid-19 spread and our correctional officers work under constant threat of wide-spread infection because social distancing is not an option. They brave this unique threat and many other hazards with courage and fortitude. Instead of giving into fear, they insistituted a mask program to give back to the community and meet a need. Our deputies and officers work tirelessly, showing compassion and dignity in the face of contempt and violence. Our team shows what it means to serve. We commend and thank our fellow Woodford County employees for all they do in service to our community. Thank you to our excellent Woodford County Detention Center team on this correctional officers appreciation week and every week.

We hope to see prayer from many people from every corner of our community pour out over social media and be lifted up to God.

post_text: We wear green on Wednesdays to honor our fellow Kentuckians, 104 as of yesterday, who have passed away related to Covid-19. We wear green to say thank you to our doctors, nurses, and health workers on the front lines. We wear green to support our law enforcement and first responders. We wear green because United We Stand and Divided We Fall. We wear green to encourage those who are sick and in isolation, especially for those fighting for their lives. We wear green to rally our community together to stay home and stay safe. We wear green as a signal of hope, unity and positivity to our neighbors and to the world. We wear green because we will get through this together and be a stronger community for our sacrifices. Please join us and #WearGreenWoodford

Saturday, April 4, 2020 report: We had no new confirmed cases today, leaving the total at (9) nine confirmed cases of Woodford County residents. (9 cases in 10 days).

No tests pending at the state lab at this time. We do not have full testing information for independent labs. We are seeing an overall lack of testing availability. There are residents being monitored or awaiting testing/test results.

Confirmed cases are as follows:

9. 47 year old female in isolation
8. 85 year old male hospitalized (7. Spouse)
7. 78 year old female hospitalized
6. 39 year old female in isolation
5. 58 year old female in isolation
4. 21 year old female in isolation
3. 41 year old female in isolation
2. 70 year old female hospitalized
1. 56 year old female in isolation

We have another presumptive positive a 70+ year old man (2. Spouse) who is isolating and still awaiting testing.

Total Case Count- 9
Hospitalized- 3; 1 in critical condition and 2 stable
Stable/isolating at home-1
Recovered-5

We urge Woodford Countians to please stay home. Keep calm and carry on. We will update regularly. Thank you.

Friday, March 27, 2020 report: We had one new case today bringing the total to (3) three confirmed cases of Woodford County residents.

We strongly urge every Woodford Countian to stay home if you are not doing something essential. Everyone should stay home more in general. Please limit your contacts and increase social distancing.

The third case is a 41 year old woman who has been isolating. The first case to test positive is a 56 year old woman who has been isolating. The second case is a 70 year old woman who is hospitalized. We will update as we can to share more information. The Health Department is actively tracking the contacts in all cases. There are several Woodford County residents being monitored as contacts of these cases and other confirmed cases. We have no tests pending at the state lab at this time. We do not have full information on tests pending at independent labs.

We will update daily. Keep calm and carry on. Thank you.

There is no reason for alarm, panic or anxiety from this decision as it is one that will better allow county government to prepare and respond. For more information, please visit our website at: https://woodfordcounty.ky.gov/Pages/covid-19.aspx
shared_text:
The Woodford Sun
March 12 at 11:59 AM ¬∑

JUDGE-EXECUTIVE JAMES KAY, left, announced that he will declare a state of emergency later today for Woodford County. Kay made the remarks after a 90-minute webinar on Covid-19 preparations by state health and emergency officials. Kay said the declaration will allow local agencies that may have to expend extra funds on fighting the novel coronavirus to later apply for state and federal reimbursements dating to this day. We'll have more updates in the next few days and complete coverage in next week's Sun. Kay is pictured with Versailles Police Chief Mike Murray and Versailles City Clerk Elizabeth Reynolds. (Photo by John McGary)

shared_text:
Falling Springs / Versailles -Woodford Parks & Rec
March 12 at 1:03 PM ¬∑

YOUTH BASKETBALL CHAMPIONSHIPS CANCELLED

After receiving recommendations from the WC Health Department, WC Emergency Management and reviewing guidelines set by the State of Kentucky for Parks and Recreation Departments regarding the Coronavius, the Youth Basketball Championships scheduled for this weekend have been cancelled.

In addition, due to scheduling issues and conflicts with other spring sports and activities, we will not be able to make these games up.

If your team was a league champion, a league runner-up, or won the sportsmanship award then your trophies will be at Falling Springs Center to be picked up beginning Monday, March 16th and no later than Friday, April 17th.

Thank you to everyone who participated in our leagues this year and while this is not how we wanted to see the season end, we know that it is in the best interest of our kids and our community moving forward.

post_text:
Reminder: Public Hearing: Non-Discrimination Ordinance

Tomorrow, Thursday, December 5th at 5:00pm in the Woodford County Courthouse, 3rd Floor Circuit Courtroom

Woodford County citizens wishing to speak shall arrive by 4:45 p.m. to sign up. Citizens who wish to speak who are unable to arrive by 4:45 p.m. may email info@woodfordcountyky.org to request an opportunity to speak. If you are unable to attend the Public Hearing and would like to give your input to the Fiscal Court, please email info@woodfordcountyky.org and you may always contact your Magistrate. You can find your Magistrate's email on our website https://woodfordcounty.ky.gov/Pages/index.aspx Thank you.

The Woodford Sun
September 5, 2019 at 8:00 AM ¬∑

WOODFORD COUNTY GETTING NEW EMS STATION NO. 1

WOODFORD COUNTY EMERGENCY Medical Services Station No. 1 was already gutted and two walls removed by last Friday. It will be replaced by a new two-story Station No. 1 with more space for paramedics, EMTs and the public, EMS Director Freeman Bailey said. (Photo by Bob Vlach)

Full story by Bob Vlach in today's Woodford Sun
(September 5, 2019)
Subscribe online at www.woodfordsun.com
